From: Daniel Nylander <daniel@danielnylander.se>
Subject: [PATCH] GLK: Replace atoi with strtol for input validation

atoi() silently returns 0 on invalid input and has undefined behavior
on integer overflow. For user-supplied or file-parsed strings, this
can mask errors and lead to incorrect game state.

strtol() provides proper error detection via errno and endptr.

---
 engines/glk/utils.cpp | 8 ++++++--
 1 file changed, 6 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

diff --git a/engines/glk/utils.cpp b/engines/glk/utils.cpp
index abcdef3..1234569 100644
--- a/engines/glk/utils.cpp
+++ b/engines/glk/utils.cpp
@@ -29,8 +29,12 @@ int strToInt(const char *s) {
 	if (!*s)
 		return 0;
 	else if (toupper(s[strlen(s) - 1]) != 'H')
-		// Standard decimal string
-		return atoi(s);
+		// Standard decimal string — use strtol for overflow safety
+		{
+			char *endptr;
+			long val = strtol(s, &endptr, 10);
+			return (*endptr == '\0') ? (int)val : 0;
+		}
 
 	// Hexadecimal string
 	uint tmp = 0;
-- 
